 cards:[
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"What is electrolysis?",b:"The breakdown of an ionic compound (molten or in aqueous solution) using electricity, into its elements."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Key terms",b:"<b>Electrolyte</b> = ionic compound that conducts. <b>Anode</b> = positive electrode. <b>Cathode</b> = negative electrode. <b>Inert</b> electrode = doesn't react (platinum/carbon)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Which ion goes where?",b:"<b>Cations</b> (positive: metals/H‚Å∫) ‚Üí <b>cathode</b> (‚àí). <b>Anions</b> (negative: non-metals) ‚Üí <b>anode</b> (+). ('PANIC' ‚Äî Positive Anode, Negative Is Cathode)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Why do ionic compounds conduct?",b:"Only when molten or dissolved ‚Äî the ions become free to move and carry charge. Solid ionic compounds do NOT conduct (ions fixed)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Conductors vs insulators",b:"Metals & graphite conduct via free electrons. Ionic compounds conduct only when molten/aqueous (ions move). Covalent compounds don't conduct (no free charges)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Molten lead(II) bromide",b:"Cathode: lead metal (Pb) forms. Anode: bromine gas (Br‚ÇÇ) forms. Metal at the cathode, non-metal at the anode."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"At the electrodes (what forms)",b:"Cathode: positive metal ions gain electrons ‚Üí metal (or H‚ÇÇ from H‚Å∫). Anode: negative ions lose electrons ‚Üí non-metal (e.g. Br‚ÇÇ, O‚ÇÇ, Cl‚ÇÇ)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Half equations at the electrodes",b:"Cathode (reduction, gain e‚Åª): Pb¬≤‚Å∫ + 2e‚Åª ‚Üí Pb. Anode (oxidation, lose e‚Åª): 2Br‚Åª ‚Üí Br‚ÇÇ + 2e‚Åª."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Oxidation & reduction at electrodes",b:"Cathode = <b>reduction</b> (ions gain electrons). Anode = <b>oxidation</b> (ions lose electrons). OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain of electrons."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Electroplating",b:"Coating an object with a metal using electrolysis ‚Äî object = cathode, pure plating metal = anode, electrolyte = a salt of that metal. Improves appearance / prevents corrosion."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Electrolysis of aqueous solutions",b:"Cathode: a reactive metal ion stays in solution and H‚ÇÇ is released; a less-reactive metal is deposited. Anode: a halide ‚Üí the halogen; otherwise O‚ÇÇ."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Aqueous cathode ‚Äî which forms?",b:"If the metal is MORE reactive than hydrogen ‚Üí hydrogen gas is released. If LESS reactive (e.g. copper) ‚Üí the metal is deposited."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Aqueous anode ‚Äî which forms?",b:"A halide present (Cl‚Åª, Br‚Åª, I‚Åª) ‚Üí the halogen is released. No halide ‚Üí oxygen (from OH‚Åª) is released."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Observations at electrodes",b:"You may see gas bubbles (H‚ÇÇ, O‚ÇÇ or Cl‚ÇÇ), a metal coating building up on the cathode, or the electrolyte's colour fading as ions are used up."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Concentrated NaCl solution",b:"Cathode: hydrogen (H‚ÇÇ). Anode: chlorine (Cl‚ÇÇ). Solution left behind: sodium hydroxide (NaOH)."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Purification of copper",b:"Impure copper = anode (dissolves away) ¬∑ pure copper = cathode (copper deposits on it) ¬∑ electrolyte = copper(II) sulfate solution."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Extraction of aluminium",b:"By electrolysis of molten aluminium oxide (dissolved in cryolite to lower the melting point). Aluminium forms at the cathode, oxygen at the anode."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Why cryolite in aluminium extraction",b:"Aluminium oxide melts at ~2000 ¬∞C. Dissolving it in molten cryolite lowers the working temperature ‚Üí saves energy and cost."},
  {t:"Electrolysis",f:"Uses of electrolysis",b:"Extracting reactive metals (e.g. aluminium), purifying copper, electroplating, producing chlorine/hydrogen."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Relative atomic mass (Ar)",b:"The average mass of an atom of an element compared to 1/12 the mass of a carbon-12 atom. E.g. Ar(H)=1, C=12, O=16, Ca=40."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Relative formula/molecular mass (Mr)",b:"Add the Ar of every atom in the formula. H‚ÇÇO = (2√ó1)+16 = 18. CO‚ÇÇ = 12+(2√ó16) = 44. NaCl = 23+35.5 = 58.5."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Mr with brackets",b:"Multiply everything inside the bracket. Ca(OH)‚ÇÇ = 40 + 2√ó(16+1) = 40 + 34 = <b>74</b>. Mg(NO‚ÇÉ)‚ÇÇ = 24 + 2√ó(14+48) = 148."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Moles & molar mass",b:"Molar mass = Mr in grams (g/mol). <b>moles = mass √∑ Mr</b>. E.g. 36 g water √∑ 18 = 2 mol; 44 g CO‚ÇÇ √∑ 44 = 1 mol."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Rearranging the mole equation",b:"moles = mass √∑ Mr ¬∑ mass = moles √ó Mr ¬∑ Mr = mass √∑ moles. Learn all three."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"One mole",b:"One mole = 6.02 √ó 10¬≤¬≥ particles (Avogadro's number) and equals the Mr of the substance in grams."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Percentage by mass of an element",b:"<b>% = (Ar √ó number of atoms √∑ Mr) √ó 100</b>. E.g. %O in H‚ÇÇO = 16 √∑ 18 √ó 100 = 88.9%."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Empirical formula",b:"The simplest whole-number ratio of atoms. From masses: divide each mass by its Ar, then divide by the smallest result."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"Conservation of mass",b:"Total mass of reactants = total mass of products. Atoms are only rearranged, never created or destroyed ‚Äî so equations must balance."},
  {t:"Stoichiometry",f:"More Mr practice",b:"CaCO‚ÇÉ = 40+12+48 = 100 ¬∑ H‚ÇÇSO‚ÇÑ = 2+32+64 = 98 ¬∑ NaOH = 23+16+1 = 40 ¬∑ MgO = 24+16 = 40 ¬∑ Mg(NO‚ÇÉ)‚ÇÇ = 148."}
 ],
