  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Circle: area & circumference",b:"Area = <b>œÄr¬≤</b> ¬∑ Circumference = <b>2œÄr</b> (or œÄd)."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Area of 2D shapes",b:"Triangle = ¬Ω¬∑b¬∑h ¬∑ Parallelogram = b¬∑h ¬∑ Trapezium = ¬Ω(a+b)¬∑h ¬∑ Rectangle = l¬∑w."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Volume of a prism / cylinder",b:"Prism = cross-sectional area √ó length. Cylinder = <b>œÄr¬≤h</b>. Cuboid = l¬∑w¬∑h."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Volume of cone, sphere, pyramid",b:"Cone = ‚ÖìœÄr¬≤h ¬∑ Sphere = <b>4‚ÅÑ3 œÄr¬≥</b> ¬∑ Pyramid = ‚Öì √ó base area √ó height."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Surface areas",b:"Cylinder = 2œÄr¬≤ + 2œÄrh ¬∑ Sphere = 4œÄr¬≤ ¬∑ Cone (curved) = œÄrl (l = slant height)."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Surface area of a cuboid",b:"SA = 2(lw + lh + wh) ‚Äî add the areas of all six faces."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Arc length & sector area",b:"Arc = (Œ∏/360)¬∑2œÄr ¬∑ Sector area = (Œ∏/360)¬∑œÄr¬≤ (Œ∏ = angle at centre)."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Semicircle & quarter circle",b:"Semicircle area = ¬ΩœÄr¬≤ ¬∑ quarter-circle area = ¬ºœÄr¬≤. Add the straight edges if you need the perimeter."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Units ‚Äî area vs volume",b:"Area is in square units (cm¬≤, m¬≤); volume in cubic units (cm¬≥, m¬≥). 1 m¬≤ = 10 000 cm¬≤; 1 m¬≥ = 1 000 000 cm¬≥."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Compound shapes",b:"Split into simple shapes (rectangles, triangles, semicircles), find each area/volume, then add or subtract."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Hemisphere & total cone area",b:"Hemisphere volume = ‚ÖîœÄr¬≥. Total surface area of a solid cone = œÄrl + œÄr¬≤ (curved surface + circular base)."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Cone slant height (Pythagoras)",b:"The slant height l = ‚àö(r¬≤ + h¬≤). Use it in the curved surface area œÄrl."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Pythagoras' theorem",b:"For a right-angled triangle: <b>a¬≤ + b¬≤ = c¬≤</b> (c = hypotenuse). Used to find missing lengths, e.g. a cone's slant height."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Volume unit conversions",b:"1 cm¬≥ = 1000 mm¬≥ ¬∑ 1 m¬≥ = 1 000 000 cm¬≥ ¬∑ 1 litre = 1000 cm¬≥. Always check units match before calculating."},
  {t:"Mensuration",f:"Leaving answers in terms of œÄ",b:"If asked for an exact answer, don't multiply by 3.14 ‚Äî e.g. area = 25œÄ cm¬≤. Only use œÄ ‚âà 3.14 when a decimal is required."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Standard form",b:"A quadratic is <b>ax¬≤ + bx + c = 0</b> (a ‚âÝ 0). Its graph is a parabola; the solutions (roots) are where it crosses the x-axis."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Solving by factorising",b:"Make it = 0 ‚Üí factorise ‚Üí set each bracket = 0. e.g. x¬≤+2x‚àí8=0 ‚Üí (x+4)(x‚àí2)=0 ‚Üí x = ‚àí4 or 2."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Factorising when a ‚âÝ 1",b:"Split the middle term: find two numbers multiplying to a¬∑c and adding to b, e.g. 2x¬≤+7x+3 ‚Üí 2x¬≤+6x+x+3 ‚Üí (2x+1)(x+3)."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"The quadratic formula",b:"For ax¬≤+bx+c=0: <b>x = (‚àíb ¬± ‚àö(b¬≤‚àí4ac)) / 2a</b>. Use when it won't factorise neatly."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Factored form: y = a(x ‚àí h)(x ‚àí k)",b:"h and k are the <b>x-intercepts (roots)</b>. e.g. y = (x ‚àí 2)(x + 3) crosses the x-axis at x = 2 and x = ‚àí3. 'a' sets the width and direction."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Vertex form: y = a(x ‚àí h)¬≤ + k",b:"The vertex (turning point) is at <b>(h, k)</b>. Mind the signs: y = (x ‚àí 3)¬≤ ‚àí 4 has vertex (3, ‚àí4). a > 0 ‚Üí minimum, a < 0 ‚Üí maximum."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Finding the vertex",b:"Easiest from vertex form y = a(x ‚àí h)¬≤ + k ‚Üí vertex (h, k). From ax¬≤+bx+c, complete the square: x¬≤+bx+c = (x + b/2)¬≤ ‚àí (b/2)¬≤ + c, so the vertex is at x = ‚àíb/2."},
  {t:"Quadratics",f:"Roots ‚Üî factors",b:"If x = p and x = q are the roots, then y = a(x ‚àí p)(x ‚àí q). The roots are where the graph crosses the x-axis (y = 0)."}
